## 14. Firmware Rules

### Layering (mandatory separation)

HAL · drivers · platform services · domain logic · configuration · communication · diagnostics · application

No peripheral register access from domain logic.

### Ownership

Each service: responsibility, public interface, dependencies, state, error behaviour, test strategy. Minimize global mutable state.

### Determinism (safety-relevant paths)

No unbounded loops · no blocking in real-time paths · no uncontrolled dynamic allocation · no silent error suppression.

### Watchdog

Service reflects health of critical services — not generic timer kick alone.

### Protocol serialization

Never send raw compiler-dependent structs on CAN, SPI, UART, or network. Use `firmware/shared/` layouts: explicit sizes, endianness, scaling, version, CRC.

### Configuration

Vehicle behaviour in `config/vehicles/*.yaml` → binary via `tools/config_compiler`. No E30 hardcoding in common code.

### Code style

Imports at top of file (no inline imports unless documented circular dependency). Exhaustive switch on discriminated unions with `never` in default.

Layout: `firmware/shared`, `firmware/dcc/logic`, `firmware/dcc/radio` per project layout docs.

### Numeric and identity discipline (firmware)

Apply §6 numeric engineering discipline and baseline/revision identity. Engineering limits, protocol values, timeouts, scaling factors, and safety behaviour shall not appear as undocumented magic numbers. Firmware builds used in validation shall carry an identifiable version or build ID.

